GEMINI-TERMINAL(1)                 User Commands                 GEMINI-TERMINAL(1)

NAME
    gemini-terminal - Bash-only dependency-light Gemini terminal client

SYNOPSIS
    gemini-terminal [session_name]
    gemini-terminal --resume <session_name>
    gemini-terminal --list
    gemini-terminal --models
    gemini-terminal --update-models
    gemini-terminal --select-model [--save]
    gemini-terminal --test-model <model_id> [--save]
    gemini-terminal --set-api-key
    gemini-terminal --attach FILE [session_name]
    gemini-terminal --credits
    gemini-terminal --doctor
    gemini-terminal --version
    gemini-terminal --help

DESCRIPTION
    gemini-terminal is the Bash-only dependency-light edition of
    gemini-terminal-tools. It is an end-user chat client, not a curl example.
    It avoids Python while still providing interactive chat, sessions, memory,
    model listing, model testing, attachments, and human-readable logs.

    The program uses Bash, curl, and common Unix tools. JSON handling is
    best-effort because Gemini's API speaks JSON and shell is not a JSON-native
    language. The Python 3 and ncurses editions are more robust, but this
    edition exists for older or constrained systems that can still run curl over
    HTTPS.

USAGE
    First-time setup:

        gemini-terminal --set-api-key
        gemini-terminal --update-models
        gemini-terminal --select-model

    Start a timestamped chat:

        gemini-terminal

    Start or reopen a named chat:

        gemini-terminal android-backup

    Resume a named chat:

        gemini-terminal --resume android-backup

    List models:

        gemini-terminal --models

    Test a model:

        gemini-terminal --test-model gemini-2.5-flash

INPUT
    Type or paste a message, then press Ctrl+D to send. Ctrl+C exits.

RUNTIME COMMAND MODE
    During a running chat, submit a line beginning with ':' to run a local
    command instead of sending a message to Gemini. Runtime commands are not
    sent to Gemini.

    Common runtime commands:

        :help
            Show runtime command help.

        :quit
            Exit chat.

        :credits
            Show credits.

        :doctor
            Run diagnostics.

        :list
            List saved sessions.

        :rename NAME
            Rename current session/log file.

        :models
            Show model list.

        :update-models
            Refresh model cache from Google.

        :select-model
            Numbered model selector.

        :test-model MODEL
            Test one model.

        :model MODEL
            Use MODEL for the current running chat only.

        :model-save MODEL
            Use MODEL and save MODEL=... to config.

        :config
            Print config summary.

        :set KEY VALUE
            Save config value.

        :unset KEY
            Remove config key.

        :set-api-key
            Prompt for and save API key.

        :forget-api-key
            Remove GEMINI_API_KEY from config.

        :memory
            Show current memory/context.

        :clear-memory
            Clear current memory/context.

        :attach FILE
            Attach FILE to next message.

        :attachments
            List saved attachments.

        :editor
            Compose a prompt in VISUAL, EDITOR, nano, or vi and send it.

    To send a literal message beginning with ':', begin it with a backslash:

        \:this goes to Gemini

CONFIGURATION
    Shared config file:

        ~/.config/gemini-cli/config

    Important keys:

        MODEL
        CONTEXT_TURNS
        GEMINI_API_KEY
        SESSION_DIR
        ATTACHMENT_DIR
        MODEL_TEST_PROMPT
        STARTUP_NOTICE

MODEL DISCOVERY
    The model list can be updated with:

        gemini-terminal --update-models

    The raw Google model-list command is:

        curl "https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models?key=YOUR_API_KEY"

MEMORY
    The client keeps a rolling context buffer. CONTEXT_TURNS controls how many
    recent user/assistant exchanges are sent back to Gemini.

ATTACHMENTS
    The client attempts to attach files and extract fenced code blocks. Binary
    media support depends on base64 availability, model support, and API limits.

LIMITATIONS
    - Requires Bash and curl.
    - Avoids Python by design.
    - JSON parsing is best-effort without Python or jq.
    - Media attachment behavior depends on model/API support.

VERSION
    gemini-terminal version 0.4.1-bash-only

AUTHOR
